<self-uri xlink:href="http://www.scielo.br/scielo.php?script=sci_arttext&amp;pid=S0034-73292018000200208&amp;lng=en&amp;nrm=iso"></self-uri><self-uri xlink:href="http://www.scielo.br/scielo.php?script=sci_abstract&amp;pid=S0034-73292018000200208&amp;lng=en&amp;nrm=iso"></self-uri><self-uri xlink:href="http://www.scielo.br/scielo.php?script=sci_pdf&amp;pid=S0034-73292018000200208&amp;lng=en&amp;nrm=iso"></self-uri><abstract abstract-type="short" xml:lang="en"><p><![CDATA[Abstract This article seeks to re-appraise the transformation of America&#8217;s international role and its influence on the transformation of the 20th century&#8217;s global order. It focuses on a re-appraisal of US aspirations to construct a &#8220;Pax Americana&#8221; and their impact on an unprecedented peace system that was first conceptualised after 1918 but only consolidated after 1945: the cold war&#8217;s transatlantic peace order. Yet my analysis also highlights important distinctions between American conceptions and behaviour vis-à-vis Europe and the superpower&#8217;s more hierarchical and often neo-imperialist approaches to &#8220;global order&#8221; and other regions during the cold war, including East Asia and Latin America.]]></p></abstract>
